  "local_port": 37660,
  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "What are some mind-blowing phone tools that exist that most people don't know about?",
  "response": "There are several lesser-known phone tools and features that can significantly enhance your smartphone experience. Here are some mind-blowing tools and apps that many people might not be aware of:\n\n### 1. **Tasker (Android)**\n   - **What it does:** Tasker allows you to automate almost any task on your Android device. You can set up custom profiles to trigger actions based on conditions like time, location, or app usage.\n   - **Example:** Automatically turn on WiFi when you get home, send a text message to a specific contact at a certain time, or switch your phone to silent mode during meetings.\n\n### 2. **IFTTT (iOS & Android)**\n   - **What it does:** IFTTT (If This Then That) connects different apps and services to automate tasks.\n   - **Example:** Sync your Instagram photos to Google Drive, get a notification when it's about to rain, or automatically log your workouts to a spreadsheet.\n\n### 3. **Snapseed (iOS & Android)**\n   - **What it does:** Snapseed is a powerful photo editing app developed by Google. It offers professional-level editing tools.\n   - **Example:** Use the \"Selective Adjust\" tool to fine-tune specific areas of your photo, or apply the \"Glamour Glow\" filter for a soft-focus effect.\n\n### 4. **Splitwise (iOS & Android)**\n   - **What it does:** Splitwise helps you keep track of shared expenses, making it easier to split bills with friends or roommates.\n   - **Example:** Enter a group dinner bill, and Splitwise will calculate how much each person owes, sending reminders if needed.\n\n### 5. **Bixby Routines (Samsung)**\n   - **What it does:** Similar to Tasker but exclusive to Samsung devices, Bixby Routines automates tasks based on user-defined conditions.\n   - **Example:** Automatically turn on Do Not Disturb mode when you arrive at work, or open Spotify when you connect your headphones.\n\n### 6. **Forest (iOS & Android)**\n   - **What it does:** Forest helps you stay focused by planting virtual trees that grow when you avoid using your phone.\n   - **Example:** Set a timer for 25 minutes, and if you stay off your phone, a tree grows in your virtual forest. If you leave the app, the tree dies.\n\n### 7. **Vysor (Android)**\n   - **What it does:** Vysor allows you to mirror and control your Android phone from your computer.\n   - **Example:** Use your phone apps directly from your desktop, or troubleshoot your phone without touching it.\n\n### 8. **Clipboard Managers (iOS & Android)**\n   - **What it does:** Clipboard managers save everything you want to copy and paste, allowing you to access your clipboard history.\n   - **Example:** Use apps like **Clipper** (Android) or **Copied** (iOS) to save and organize copied text, links, or images for later use.\n\n### 9. **Google Lens (iOS & Android)**\n   - **What it does:** Google Lens uses your phone's camera to identify objects, text, and more, providing relevant information or actions.\n   - **Example:** Translate text in real-time, identify plants and animals, or find similar products online by scanning them with your camera.\n\n### 10. **NextDNS (iOS & Android)**\n   - **What it does:** NextDNS is a customizable DNS service that blocks ads, trackers, and malicious websites at the network level.\n   - **Example:** Set up NextDNS on your phone to block annoying ads in apps and browsers, or protect your device from phishing sites.\n\n### 11. **AutoRedial (Android)**\n   - **What it does:** Automatically redials a number until the call goes through.\n   - **Example:** Useful for calling busy customer service lines or during network congestion.\n\n### 12. **Volume Booster (iOS & Android)**\n   - **What it does:** Boosts the volume beyond the default maximum level.\n   - **Example:** Use apps like **Volume Booster GOODEV** (Android) to increase the sound output for media, calls, or notifications.\n\n### 13. **Join by JoaoApps (Android)**\n   - **What it does:** Join allows you to sync notifications, clipboard, and files between your Android device and computer.\n   - **Example:** Send text messages from your computer, or receive and respond to phone notifications directly on your desktop.\n\n### 14. **Sleep Cycle (iOS & Android)**\n   - **What it does:** Sleep Cycle analyzes your sleep patterns and wakes you up during your lightest sleep phase.\n   - **Example:** Place your phone on your mattress, and the app will monitor your movements to determine the best time to wake you up within a preset window.\n\n### 15. **Wolfram Alpha (iOS & Android)**\n   - **What it does:** Wolfram Alpha is a computational knowledge engine that provides expert-level answers to complex questions.\n   - **Example:** Use it to solve math problems, get nutritional information, or find detailed statistics on almost any topic.\n\nThese tools can greatly enhance your phone's functionality, making your life more efficient and enjoyable.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
